`PerformanceCounter.NextValue()` generates memory allocations.
OS: Windows

To reproduce:
```
var counter = new PerformanceCounter(".NET CLR Memory", "Allocated Bytes/sec", instance);

while (true)
{
       var current = counter.NextValue();
       var gc0 = GC.CollectionCount(0); //Grows endlessly (not on every iteration, but grows)

       Console.WriteLine($"Allocated bytes/sec: {current:0}, GC0 count: {gc0}");
       Thread.Sleep(500);
 }
```

Windows implementation of `PerformanceCounter` uses method `object RegistryKey.GetValue(string name)`  which is internally [allocate at least ~64Kb on every call](https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/b492409b4a1952cda4b078f800499d382e1765fc/src/Microsoft.Win32.Registry/src/Microsoft/Win32/RegistryKey.Windows.cs#L557)

I expect that `PerformanceCounter.NextValue()` will not generate memory allocations on each call. It is significant if we ask about next value several performance counters  (100, 200, etc).
